LIVENESS AND READINESS

1. Liveness Probe
Definition
A Liveness Probe checks whether the application inside the container is still alive or stuck. If the probe fails repeatedly, Kubernetes restarts the container automatically.

Why it is needed

Sometimes an application may enter a deadlock or infinite loop but the container itself is still running.

Example situations:

Thread deadlock

Application freeze

Memory leak causing unresponsiveness

Infinite loop
What Kubernetes does

If the Liveness Probe fails:

Kubernetes marks container as unhealthy

Container is killed

Container is restarted automatically
---------------------------------------------------
2. Readiness Probe
Definition

A Readiness Probe checks whether the application is ready to receive traffic. If it fails, Kubernetes stops sending requests to that pod but does NOT restart it. Why it is needed Sometimes the application is running but not ready.
Example situations:

Application still starting

Database connection not established

Cache loading

External service dependency not ready

During this time, traffic should not be routed to the pod.

What Kubernetes does

If the Readiness Probe fails:

Pod is removed from Service endpoints

Pod stops receiving traffic

Container continues running

Once probe succeeds → traffic resumes

under configserver
under management
management:
 health:
  readiness-state:
   enabled:true
  liveness-state:
   enabled:true
 endpoint:
  health:
   probes:
    enabled:true


